{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:47:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:47:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17453"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17453"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10143"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70892"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10143"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56359"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5431"},{"type":"tags","id":"5437"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23743"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23827"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70892"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPublic health officials must distinguish between different patterns of disease occurrence in populations to implement appropriate control measures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes an epidemic?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gradual increase in disease over many years","Seasonal variation in disease occurrence","Global spread of disease across continents","Sudden increase in disease occurrence above expected levels","Constant presence of disease in a population"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Esudden increase in disease occurrence above expected levels\u003C/strong\u003E is the defining characteristic of an epidemic. This represents a significant deviation from the baseline or expected number of cases in a specific population and time period.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGradual increase in disease over many years\u003C/strong\u003E describes a secular trend, which reflects long-term changes in disease patterns rather than the sudden increase seen in epidemics.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeasonal variation in disease occurrence\u003C/strong\u003E refers to predictable fluctuations in disease rates that follow regular patterns throughout the year.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobal spread of disease across continents\u003C/strong\u003E defines a pandemic, which occurs when an epidemic extends internationally across multiple regions.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConstant presence of disease in a population\u003C/strong\u003E characterises an endemic condition where disease occurs at a baseline or expected rate within a population.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these patterns helps public health officials identify outbreaks quickly and implement appropriate control measures. An epidemic may be confined to a local area or spread to become a pandemic, but the key feature is the unexpected increase above normal levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An epidemic occurs when there is a sudden increase in disease cases beyond what is normally expected in a defined population.","Endemic diseases maintain a steady state within a given population with generally predictable patterns.","A pandemic is a global epidemic affecting multiple countries or continents simultaneously."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Riley LW. Differentiating Epidemic from Endemic or Sporadic Infectious Disease Occurrence. Microbiol Spectr. 2019;7(4):10.1128/microbiolspec.ame-0007-2019. doi:10.1128/microbiolspec.AME-0007-2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56359"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17453"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56359"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T15:01:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T15:02:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10143"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70892"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"